		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Dark Souls: My (new) All-Time Favorite Game.
				</h2>
				

						
							
							
							
						
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1829698">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Just a PSA to anyone who might not have played this absolute gem of a game.  It's basically a cross between The Legend of Zelda, Bushido Blade, Mike Tyson's punch-out, and the original Castlevania.  The combat mechanics are deep and the content design is amazing.  It's notorious for its challenge, but it's somewhat overblown in that regard.  If you play the game thoughtfully and carefully, you can often make predictions and be rewarded for creativity.  There's a blind &quot;Let's Play&quot; on youtube by user &quot;Kay Plays&quot; that exemplifies this approach.  Here's a <a href="http://youtu.be/c_TpExyw710?t=6m44s" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">particularly awesome segment</a> where she encounters a very difficult enemy and makes heavy use of the environment to optimize her chance of winning.<br />
<br />
Here are some of the reasons why Dark Souls is awesome:<br />
<br />
<ul><li style="">There Is More Than One Way To Do It.  Almost always, there are multiple viable tactics for dealing with any given situation, from overcoming environmental hazards to defeating bosses.  There are some principles that apply generally (observe the environment, learn the enemy attack patterns, stay alive first and attack only when you have an opening), and there are often certain weapons and techniques that are more effective than others, but that's it.</li><li style="">Near-perfect balance between gear, level, and player skill.  Level matters.  Gear matters.  It feels awesome to have your character get stronger and get more powerful weapons and armor.  But level and gear aren't enough, you still have to have skill to win.  And in fact, skill can often compensate for weak gear and low level.  The game can be beaten at level one.  There's a <a href="http://www.reddit.com/r/OneBros/?2" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">whole subreddit</a> dedicated to this pastime.</li><li style="">Fantastic level design.  Each level presents a sequence of unique challenges.  Usually the initial content is very linear, sometimes with branching, and sometimes with buildings and basements and other non-linear elements.  There will be checkpoints along the way, like in classic platform games, so when you die you'll only have to start from the most recent checkpoint (bonfire).  There are minibosses and other non-respawning enemies.  Eventually you'll open up shortcuts that will let you bypass the trickiest areas.  And finally, you'll eventually discover shortcuts from later areas to earlier areas.  The entire world fits together like a puzzle and once you've unlocked all the shortcuts, getting from place to place is very easy.  By the time the world is big enough that running around would be a huge pain, you'll have the ability to warp.  And most importantly:  once you know your way around the world, you realize there are tons of opportunities for &quot;sequence skipping.&quot;  This makes the game feel truly &quot;open world&quot; even though it's designed to accommodate a very linear playthrough.</li><li style="">Rewarding challenge and memorable bosses.  Hard to talk about this without spoiling anything (spoilers: <a href="http://youtu.be/YvOUPdBgV1Y?t=9m31s" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">1</a>, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sgszgbjfBcE" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">2</a>, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ctW277Kpcv0" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">3</a>)</li><li style="">Emphasis on exploration and combat.  The game is dense with the best kind of gameplay content.  There aren't any &quot;quests&quot; like is typical of RPGs.  You never have to find 10 green chicken feathers or deliver a donkey scrotum from point A to point B.  There are some gorgeous views and fantastic set designs, but very little is designed just to run through and admire.  (There is a giant city, which is suitably giant and does take a long time to run through, but that's the exception)</li><li style="">Consistent, surreal theming.  Plot that stays out of the way of the fun.  There are very few NPCs and most of their dialogue is streamlined.  It's suitable to the theming and characterization, without any need for dramaticization (but they do seriously all have creepy laughs).  The game starts you off with a simple goal:  go ring a bell.  Then you run into a guy who says &quot;oh yeah there are actually 2 bells you have to ring.&quot;  Ringing both bells is the end of Act I (30-40+ hours).  You get a short cutscene that shows you where to go next.</li><li style="">Fantastic replayability.  Due to that balance of gear, level, and skill I mentioned earlier, along with the general open-worldiness, means that there are dozens of different ways to play the game.  You can see how many sequence skips you can make to optimize your power to to completely wreck the early-game bosses that gave you so much trouble on your first playthrough.  Or you can go the opposite direction and stick to a low soul level, re-discover the original challenge and find new challenges.  You can play as a pryomaniac axe-murder or a heavily-armored knight.  </li></ul><br />
<br />
Generally speaking, people discourage spoilers, especially content spoilers, when playing Dark Souls and that's true but I don't think it will &quot;totally ruin the experience.&quot;  One thing to realize though is that missing little bits of content like items and armor is not likely to screw you in the way that it can in some other games.  This is partly due to the game's fantastic, 3-dimensional world and level design that is full of shortcuts and areas that loop around and connect to each other.  Typically, once you get past the most challenging part of a level, you'll have an opportunity to open a shortcut to bypass that section the next time you come through.  Then when it seems like you've progressed through several zones, you'll find yourself back where you started.  This means that even if you miss something, it's not too hard to go back and find it later.  Additionally, finding every weapon and armor in the game is mostly just going to leave you with a cluttered inventory of equipment that you never bother to use.  Increasing your character's power is much more about upgrading weapons with commodity upgrade materials than finding Excalibur or Ragnarok.  Though there are a few items available early in the game that can obscure this dynamic (Drake Sword, Black Knight Sword)<br />
<br />
The main exception to this &quot;no content is truly missable&quot; rule are NPC storylines, which can be permanently screwed if you progress past a certain point without fulfilling requirements.  But unlike some games, NPC sublots aren't a huge part of Dark Souls.  Also, this game has enormous replayability.  Even though I am pushing 200 hours for my first playthrough and have just two bosses left, one is the final boss for the game and the other is the final boss of the DLC, now that I know the game pretty well I could get through it again much more quickly if I specifically wanted to try and complete a particular NPC questline.<br />
<br />
Given that this is a wizard forum, I will point out that the game is VERY melee-oriented.  That said, there's a great variety of spells in the game, with a ride range of utility in and out of combat.  There are several varieties of projectile as well as mists, &quot;burning-hands&quot; type spells, and a few PBAoE attacks.  There's even a charm spell (though I've never used it).  In fact a Sorcerer build is one of the best builds for speedrunning.  But this is definitely not D&amp;D, there aren't 100 different utility spells to accomplish everything under the sun, and no godly one-hit-kill kind of spells.  Even though you can configure builds to do ridiculously powerful spells in the right situations, that usually involves doing things like using a buff that drains health and a ring that buffs your damage output when you are low health (consider the implications of that combo).  There's also no real crowd control spells, barring a few knockbacks and that one charm spell (which is fairly limited use).  Crowd control in this game primarily has to be done via the environment or pulling one at a time.<br />
<br />
Anyway I could go on forever singing this game's praises, and since the game is like 4 years old at this point I'm sure no one cares, so I'll just leave it there.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
