			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Dark Souls: My (new) All-Time Favorite Game.
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1829787">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Ikeya</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=ef035035ca80ac30c4a1f3dbbb883709&amp;p=1829770#post1829770" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">On the flip side, I am not a fan of Dark Souls or Dark Souls 2.  If you are a fan of &quot;fair&quot; game play, you will likely find Dark Souls frustrating on your first play through.  Dark Souls is a series that strongly favors of what I'd call &quot;fair in hindsight.&quot;  That is, once you are aware of the ins and outs of a level and the nuances of monsters you fight, it is fair and you will generally feel accomplished standing atop your conquests.  You will also have a mountain of failures from the game killing you with a cheap shot suddenly and unexpectedly.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>The truth is, I did not find this to be true, for the most part, except for bosses and maybe Sen's fortress.  Generally, I had just enough HP, estus (healing), and general ability to stay alive that deaths while exploring new areas were very rare.  I played Dark Souls the way I solo'd Dalnir or The Hole as a Magician in EQ:  Very slowly and very cautiously.  <br />
<br />
Cheap shots?  I can't deny there were some, but they were pretty few and far between from my perspective.  FAR more deaths came when I got over-confident and rushed into something.<br />
<br />
On bosses, yeah I died a lot, but in most of those cases the deaths felt like deaths in Mega Man or losing in Mike Tyson's Punchout.  A player with really quick reflexes and observational skills can probably beat Piston Honda on the first try, but the average player is probably going to lose a couple of times before their reflexes are up to the challenge.  And consider Mike Tyson himself: Tyson's uppercut only gives you a couple of frames to dodge and counter.  It's extremely hard to pull off.  The vast majority of players will not be able to beat Tyson on the first try.  Even if they recognize the tell, they may not have the reflexes to dodge it right away.  But in theory, you COULD be fast enough to do it.  Most Dark Souls bosses are hard in the way Mike Tyson is hard, though they tend to require more complex observational skills and reflexes.  There are a few bullshit moments, but given how the rest of the game was so awesome I really couldn't let those drag me down.<br />
<br />
It is an action game, not really and RPG.  Action RPG I guess.  The combat itself is fairly deliberate and slow-paced for an action game, but it's definitely not a tactical game.  I often prefer turn-based games (no matter how challenging) because I don't like having to train my reflexes and such.  But in this game the rewards were worth it to me.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
