			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Dark Souls: My (new) All-Time Favorite Game.
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1829788">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Wool</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=ef035035ca80ac30c4a1f3dbbb883709&amp;p=1829772#post1829772" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I was under the impression Goladus was already a Demon Souls fan. I haven't played Dark Souls yet, so I don't know what, other than the different world structure, would possibly be better about it.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Did not play Demon's Souls.  I looked at the 3 from a 30,000 foot view and picked the middle entry, largely for the connected-world and themes of discovery and exploration.  I haven't played DkS2 yet either, though a friend lent me a copy.  My personal impression is that most of the love is divided between Dark Souls and Demon's Souls.  While some people like Dark Souls II the best, they seem to be less passionate than the other two camps but this might just be my bias.  The general attitude of DkS1 players seems to be that DkS2 is &quot;better than most games out there but no DkS1&quot;  It seems like the core gameplay mechanics and difficulty levels are similar between all three games.<br />
<br />
One other thing I've since read about Dark Souls is that the death penalty is mild compared to the other two.  When you die, you leave all your souls and (soft) humanity on your bloodstain and respawn, hollow, at the last bonfire you rested at.  If you die again before touching your bloodstain, those souls and humanity will be permanently lost.  There's no other penalty like a semi-permanent reduction of HP unless you are specifically cursed.  This means there are a variety of ways to mitigate death penalties.  It effectively discourages hoarding of souls, encouraging you to spend them on anything you might find useful to progress.  Why not spend them on firebombs or poison arrows or titanite, etc.?
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
