		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Dark Souls: My (new) All-Time Favorite Game.
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1829806">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				 There isn't really anything going on other than exploration
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>If you go look online for the cheapest, fastest ways to beat the game it will probably get repetitive, but it's pretty trivial to just ignore the few imbalanced mechanics and just play in a way that is fun.  In <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ng9BBk2Z5dY" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">this video</a>, Kay expresses regret at one point that she passed up a great opportunity to kick one of the mooks into the fire.  That's exactly the right mindset.  You'll note that she tries a variety of different weapons as she proceeds.  Each one has different strengths and weaknesses and changes the way you experience the game.  Given the same number of hits, a battle axe is more likely to stagger an opponent than a katana, though they will do similar damage.  A long sword will deal less damage, but will attack faster and consume less stamina per swing.  This will change your tactics-- will change the way you defeat enemies.  It will also make some more challenging than others in an organic, natural way (not merely a rock-paper-scissors)<br />
<br />
And then there's the actual content in the levels themselves.  Did you watch that video I linked in the first post?  I am sure you can recognize creative gameplay when you see it.  If you refuse to watch it, I'll just post a narration here to demonstrate just how much happens in that relatively short amount of time.  Note that this isn't a boss, it's a mini-boss at best.  The boss encounters I linked above are perhaps a bit less creative, but pretty much impossible to call repetitive.<br />
<br />
==<br />
<br />
Kay sees a big knight.  Cannot lock on, wonders if it is friendly.  Turns out player was just a little out of lock-on range, and the knight turns around aggressively.  Definitely not friendly!<br />
<br />
1.  Knight attacks and despite the surprise, she was ready enough to block.  Blocking that attack cost a lot of stamina.  (Mechanic note:  stronger shield means less stamina would have been lost)<br />
<br />
2.  She retreats to recover and find a better position.  She tries to stay out of range and block attacks when he gets close.  Notice that most of the knight's attacks are draining less stamina than his opening thrust.  At one point, she heals when she has enough time between attacks.<br />
<br />
3.  She discovers a location where she can drop from above and perform some easy plunging attacks.  But this only works twice before the knight is high enough to attack her.  (She takes damage)<br />
<br />
4.  Tries to see if a strong attack will knock his shield out of the way (which, with her choice of weapon, does tend to work against the other enemies with shield's she has encountered up to that point).<br />
<br />
5.  That fails, but she did manage to deal some decent damage, but takes some at the same time since she had two-handed her weapon (putting away the shield).  She re-readies her shield, but the next blocked attack staggers her since her stamina ran out.  Luckily, the knight was finished with his move and had to recover himself.<br />
<br />
6.  She takes the opportunity to climb a nearby ladder to a roof, planning to drop some bombs on his head.  Unfortunately, the knight not only does not follow her up the ladder but circles around to the other side of the building, where he is shielded by a platform.<br />
<br />
7.  There are two firebomb-throwing mooks on the platform.  One attacks and she kicks him off the ledge, forgetting that this particular ledge was only 8 feet down or so, which doesn't kill him.  So now the firebomb mook and the black knight are both wandering around under the platform.  She goes and kicks the other mook off the platform to his death (with awareness that yes, this one is over a huge pit).<br />
<br />
8.  She observes the two enemies below and waits to see what they will do, in particular hoping that the firebomb guy will come away so she can get rid of him easily.  He does, and in fact follows and climbs up the ladder.  At this point she's now learned that some enemies can climb ladders while others probably can't (in this case, it's true that the Black Knight won't climb the ladder)).<br />
<br />
9.  He's a very easy kill one-on-one, which makes sense given this is the first real zone in the game and his main role is to throw firebombs from above not engage in melee.<br />
<br />
10.  She then targets the Black Knight and executes a solid plunging attack, which staggers the knight briefly giving her time to immediately run back around to the other side of the building to climb back up.<br />
<br />
11.  She attempts two more plunging attacks, which still hit for good damage but didn't cause the same staggering as the first one.  The first time, she blocks a few attacks with her shield while retreating back to the roof.  The second attack, she seems to just graze him and this time he is able to attack and deal some serious damage before she can make it back to the roof and safety.<br />
<br />
12.  Runs out of healing.  She makes one final attempt at a plunging attack, this one misses entirely and she gets hit again.  Down to ~15% health with no healing left.  Additionally, this time she does not make it back to the ladder ahead of the knight, so has to evade until she can get back up the ladder and figure out what to do next.<br />
<br />
13.  Tries all her available projectiles, but none of them do very much damage (his shield is blocking all of them).  Firebomb does 12, arrow 2, throwing dagger 1, etc.<br />
<br />
14.  She jumps over to a ledge (one that I didn't even notice) to try and get a better angle.  She waits until his back is turned, then throws a firebomb, this time for 40 damage.  Might be enough to kill him, but she has only 3 left. <br />
<br />
15.  Nope.  He blocks 2 of them again, and it might not have been enough anyway (Black Knights are actually quite resistant to fire-- there's lore for why this is)<br />
<br />
16.  Goes for broke, tries a plunging attack and completely misses, taking some falling damage in the process meaning she is down to about 10% health with no healing.<br />
<br />
17.  Tries one last plunging attack, HITS but the knight still lives!<br />
<br />
18.  Block, block, block...  Goes for broke for real with a jumping attack hoping that he has so little health that it'll finish him off.<br />
<br />
19.  And it does!  The knight disappears in a blast of energy.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
