		</div>
		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Dark Souls: My (new) All-Time Favorite Game.
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1829809">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Huh, that's strange. I could have sworn you brought up one of these games before in a conversation about how poor modern games are as one of the few you approved of. I get this stuff mixed up a lot, I guess. It was probably a suggestion someone made to you, or something.<br />
<br />
That death penalty sounds much like the one from Demon's Souls by the way. The games are good at teaching you to be careful and conditioning the player to actually care about their surroundings, while not making death so crushing that you just give up.<br />
<br />
I think it says interesting things about player psychology and the way games condition you to play. There aren't many games that make as good an illustration of the learning process that takes place when you play any game. A lot of games don't expect much from the player, as they are meant to be leisurely entertainment. The player actually learns to be complacent while playing them, but even then the player is still learning things. It's almost like learning a bad habit. You learn that blank is weak to fire, but it doesn't really matter so you just mash buttons. You have actually learned two things in this scenario. A Souls game will test your ability to learn and adapt as much as they test your actual gameplay skill, and does it in such a blatantly obvious way that what is going on cannot be ignored. You will learn that what you do actually does matter, and when you do something that gets you killed you will learn not to do it again. This is part of what makes them fascinating, even for people who don't really like that kind of game much. <br />
<br />
I was actually surprised at how &quot;fair&quot; the first game was, as it didn't go the route of punishing you just for the sake of pretending to be difficult. I was nervous going in for the first time, but there was almost nothing that could happen to you that you couldn't recover from. In any other game trying to be hard they would have slapped a Game Over screen in your face and forced you to start over. It was all a gradual learning process until you achieved enough mastery to get to the end. In a Souls game, you are not expected to beat a level on the first try. I think dying to a trap is probably less frustrating once you realize this. It's almost like Rogue Legacy, in that it has roguelike traits (harsh deaths), but you get to carry over things that makes the next run easier.<br />
<br />
<br />
While I am on the subject of learning and complacency, by the way, the Persona games are kind of similar. I saw a thread on neogaf the other day, where a guy was trying Persona 4 for the first time due to all the hype, but he couldn't quite grasp it. He couldn't figure out why he couldn't beat a boss. I never saw confirmation from the original poster, but the conversation seemed to imply that he was making a plethora of major mistakes all likely originating from his own assumptions about what a jrpg is. <br />
<br />
Final Fantasy, and games like it, breed complacency in the jrpg genre. The player learns without realizing it that what they do doesn't really matter, and they turn off their brain as they go through the motions. For some people this is actually part of the appeal. Older jrpgs taught players that grinding will help them surpass any obstacle, and the lesson has stuck years after it stopped being true. The &quot;defend&quot; command in particular is a stickler for me. It's always present, largely only because it always has been, but in 90% of jrpgs there is almost no reason to ever use it. It's always a little sad when a game does, and people don't realize that the reason why they are dying is because they have been taught to completely ignore one of their five possible commands.<br />
<br />
To be clear, I am not trying to denigrate Final Fantasy, or any game that doesn't demand as much from the player for that matter. These games still have things of value depending on personal preference. It's just an interesting thing to observe and understand. People are always learning things that influence their behavior, whether they realize it or not.<br />
<br />
And now you know where the annoying meme &quot;the Dark Souls of blank game genre&quot; comes from.<br />
<br />
P.S. From what I can tell, the people who like Dark Souls 2 the most are the people who played Dark Souls 2 first.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
				<!-- edit note -->
				<blockquote class="postcontent lastedited">
