				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Dark Souls: My (new) All-Time Favorite Game.
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1829908">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>QuelianSpyralshot</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=ef035035ca80ac30c4a1f3dbbb883709&amp;p=1829841#post1829841" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Directed at me or Goladus? I don't hate dark souls. I just sort of had a moment at 10 hours in that was like &quot;Ok, gameplay isn't going to change for the next 200 hours and I really don't care enough about the story to proceed.&quot; It just pushed past my patience.<br />
<br />
The game's gameplay is fine really. The enemies are all solid. There's nothing WRONG with the game. The problem is my real life is actually more interesting than the game at the moment so I'm focusing on that. We could do a lot <b>worse</b> than dark souls. I just think if they'd bothered to put some better NPC interaction in it'd have gripped me harder.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Goladus. I was replying to the misconception I had mentioned earlier in the thread.<br />
<br />
I completely understand why Souls is not for you. There are many reasons to play a game, and games are capable of providing many different things. There is a reason why modern game designed has evolved to the point it has, but in order to survive the industry as a whole tend to overspecialize in the things with a wide appeal. Souls provides to a niche that is specifically bored of standard design. The fact you generally need to put time into &quot;getting good&quot; at it is most of the appeal. And as is usually the case with a niche that is long ignored, once it surfaces again it explodes to a state arguably more widespread than it normally would be able to maintain. <br />
<br />
And so, in a few years the niche begins to die down again. I think Dark Souls is probably a little more popular than it warrants. Not because it isn't a good game, but because I don't think there are that many people that actually play it to be challenged in such a way. The excitement over finally getting what they want has created a lot of buzz and attention for something the general market would usually ignore.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
