		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Dark Souls: My (new) All-Time Favorite Game.
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1829915">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Ikeya</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=ef035035ca80ac30c4a1f3dbbb883709&amp;p=1829770#post1829770" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">On the flip side, I am not a fan of Dark Souls or Dark Souls 2.  If you are a fan of &quot;fair&quot; game play, you will likely find Dark Souls frustrating on your first play through.  Dark Souls is a series that strongly favors of what I'd call &quot;fair in hindsight.&quot;  That is, once you are aware of the ins and outs of a level and the nuances of monsters you fight, it is fair and you will generally feel accomplished standing atop your conquests.  You will also have a mountain of failures from the game killing you with a cheap shot suddenly and unexpectedly.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I think that is the most apropos, comprehensive description of From Software's design; it captures the main distinction between that design and other takes in games anyways that are more common. I like how the lore is tucked away as well rather than being overt. None of From Software's implementation of the fairness in hindsight is implemented in a way that builds throughout the game with minimal new unavoidable player ignorance of what is entailed, but that could be done and would reduce how much hindsight plays into it; if they were already familiar from naturally experienced patterns elsewhere it would not be apparent at all, which would be cool.<br />
<br />
I think the description you made uncovers why I enjoy other games that previously I did not really perceive as behaving that same way; Super Meat Boy falls into that category as well in my mind. IMO it is nice, and defensible (other than only appealing to the conclusion that `time spent having fun is never wasted`, which I agree with and find sound, but it need not stand alone) when an activity has other ancillary effects that are beneficial. Ideally in my mind a great game indirectly trains the player or helps maintain a skill that is as useful elsewhere as possible. <br />
<br />
There are not many games that achieve that well while not being mostly transparent or almost wholly simply inefficient skill training; all of the attempts at gamifying traditional  education pedagogy falls into that role, where as a good example of this being better achieved is absorbing history/trivia while playing a game from its lore; while of dubious usefulness, a Lord of the Rings game could teach the linguistic makeup of Tolkien's world that is the most interesting part of Tolkien's universe by being requisite for puzzle solving/discerning quest information.<br />
<br />
Starcraft has a lot of benefits in addition to being fun on its own; pen and paper games as well. Some augmented reality games are excellent (although somewhat dangerous in practice to the player). My ideal game would be one that teaches abstract thinking extremely well/using tools which require such due to it being required to be competitive in the game world. I really want to get as many people trained on CAD and programming, in particular formal maths as it relates to programming as that is the most efficient way to learn categories of information once the barrier to entry for understanding the language which describes it is understood, which is where most people who even manage to make it that far in maths throw in the towel I think [citation needed]. <br />
<br />
It most heavily contributes to the effective innumeracy seen in programmers that do not go on to pursue a masters or doctorate that instill/require that understanding beyond a surface level, which is tremendously regrettable as it prevents them from understanding/being able to understand papers until they trickle down in less information dense presentations, usually less effectively, and indirectly increasing the latency between new research and practice there of, usually on the order of decades thus far. Relatedly it also reduces the demographic that can implement and design more powerful analysis tools or augment existing ones well, however I think that will be ameliorated on its own in a couple of decades at least. At least at the moment it means that the potency of analysis tools which are not comparably very expensive is not readily available with a handful of exceptions, which in any case a marginal amount of users it is relevant to only make use of them.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
